      <div id="guide_body"> <img style="padding: 25px 15px; float: left;" src="OutmatchedDecklist.png"

          align="left"> <pg><br>
          <h0g>Portrait of the Eternal power base as first-place <br>
            Saturday Challenge finisher</h0g> <subhead>Nishava took first place
            at the inaugural <a href="https://eternaltournaments.com/viewtournament/46"

              target="_blank">Kaelari's Saturday Challenge</a> event <br>
            with an aggressive Combrei list entitled <a href="https://eternalwarcry.com/decks/details/BExhaKnK9VE/rakanos-weapons-are-outmatched"

              target="_blank"><i>Rakano's weapons are outmatched!</i></a> <br>
            <br>
            Let's take a look at the power base:</subhead><subhead><img id="outmatched-powerbase"

              src="OutmatchedPowerbase.jpeg" style="width: 842px;" align="left"

              width="700"><br>
          </subhead> <br>
          <br>
          <br>
          <br>
          One of the first things you might notice is that a lot of extra
          sources help to ensure Nishava has a very high probability of drawing
          enough <b>Power</b> and <b>Influence</b> to play their early units
          on <strong>Turns 1</strong> and <strong>2</strong>. <br>
          <br>
          For many decks, "extra power" means including an additional power card
          beyond the minimum of 25. But here Nishava has included no fewer than
          28. <br>
          <br>
          A full playset of <i>Initiate of the Sands</i> brings the total
          number of <strong>Power</strong> sources in the deck to 32. <h1g><img

              id="outmatched-powerbase" src="OutmatchedChartTrimmedInitiate.jpeg"

              alt="Influence Chart" title="Influence Chart">Time Quickens</h1g>
          The <b>Influence Chart</b> tells us that the pilot of this deck has a
          91% chance of holding <img src="../epc/icon-time.png" alt="Time" title="Justice"

            style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"> in their opening hand when going
          first, enough to play <i>Initiate of the Sands</i> on <strong>Turn 1</strong>.
          <br>
          <br>
          This conveniently sets the table for playing one of the deck's twelve
          powerful 3-drops as early as <strong>Turn 2</strong>: <em>Kosul
            Battlemage</em>, <em>Unseen Commando</em>, or <em>Valkyrie
            Enforcer</em> - each of which has an influence cost of <img src="../epc/icon-justice.png"

            alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"><img

            src="../epc/icon-justice.png" alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;">.
          <br>
          <br>
          We can see that even at this early stage, the odds of drawing <img src="../epc/icon-justice.png"

            alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"><img

            src="../epc/icon-justice.png" alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;">
          are quite good: 77% after two draws. After three draws the chances are
          even better, at 83%. <img id="outmatched-powerbase" src="OutmatchedChartTrimmedJJ.jpeg"

            alt="Influence Chart" title="Influence Chart"><h1g>Mind Over Body</h1g>
          A 3-drop on Turn 2 makes for a strong start, but what if <i>Initiate
            of the Sands</i> doesn't&nbsp; show up in the first couple of draws?<br>
          <br>
          Nishava still has plenty of options even without <em>Initiate. </em><br>
          <br>
          <em>Crownwatch Paladin </em>(<img src="../epc/icon-justice.png" alt="Justice"

            title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;">) or <em>Awakened
            Student </em>(<em><img src="../epc/icon-time.png" alt="Time" title="Justice"

              style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"><img src="../epc/icon-justice.png"

              alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"></em>)
          on <strong>Turn 2</strong> are likely to frustrate your opponent just
          as much if not more so. <br>
          <br>
          The odds of drawing enough resources<strong></strong> to play either
          of these units on curve is quite high: 87% or better.<img id="outmatched-powerbase"

            src="OutmatchedChartTrimmedJJ.jpeg" alt="Influence Chart" title="Influence Chart">
          Nishava's&nbsp; chances of playing <em>Crownwatch Paladin </em>are
          slightly better than for <em>Awakened Student</em>, and the <strong>Power
            Odds Table</strong> tells us why. <br>
          <br>
          To play <em>Awakened Student</em>&nbsp; you need to draw at least two
          <strong>Power</strong> and also two different <strong>Influence</strong>
          sources:&nbsp; both&nbsp; <img src="../epc/icon-time.png" alt="Time"

            title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"> and&nbsp; <img

            src="../epc/icon-justice.png" alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;">.&nbsp;
          For Nishava's first-place build, the combined odds of meeting each of
          these requirements after two draws are 87%.&nbsp; <br>
          <br>
          Although <em>Crownwatch Paladin</em> requires the same amount of <strong>Power</strong>
          - her <strong>Influence</strong> cost is less demanding, at a single
          <img src="../epc/icon-justice.png" alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;">.
          The table tells us that the combined odds for these requirements after
          two draws are a comfortable 91%.&nbsp; <br>
          
          <h1g>Subhead</h1g>Nishava has constructed a very reliable, low-risk
          power base for <em>Rakano's weapons are unmatched!, </em>and this
          undoubtedly contributed to their success in <strong>Kaelari's
            Saturday Challenge</strong>. <br>
          <br>
          An aggressive deck like this one needs to be dropping units right out
          of the gate, and for the most part Nishava has a 76% chance or better
          of doing just that on Turns 1, 2 and 3 .&nbsp; <br>
          <br>
          The exception is <em>Teacher of Humility, </em>a powerful 2-cost <img

            src="../epc/icon-time.png" alt="Time" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"><img

            src="../epc/icon-time.png" alt="Time" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;">
          unit that has made quite an impression in the early <strong>Fall of
            Argenport</strong> meta. Nishava has chosen to prioritize their <img

            src="../epc/icon-justice.png" alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;"><img

            src="../epc/icon-justice.png" alt="Justice" title="Justice" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;">
          units over <em>Teacher, </em>such that the odds of <br>
